
India's agricultural sector employs over 50% of the national workforce, yet the very people who grow the nation's food remain among its most economically vulnerable. At the heart of this paradox lies a broken supply chain — one that systematically strips farmers of the value they create and channels it to layers of predatory intermediaries.

1.1  The 25–35% Profit Gap: A Structural Injustice
According to NITI Aayog (Doubling Farmers' Income, Volume V), Indian farmers currently receive only 25–35% of the final consumer price of their produce. The remaining 65–75% is absorbed by a chain of middlemen — commission agents (arhatias), local traders, aggregators, and transporters — none of whom add proportional value.

A farmer sells tomatoes at ₹8/kg. The same tomatoes reach the urban consumer at ₹40/kg. The farmer's share: 20%. The intermediary chain's share: 80%.

This gap is not a market anomaly — it is a structural outcome of information asymmetry. Farmers have no reliable, real-time access to market prices. They sell blind, accepting whatever price the local trader offers because they have no alternative. This is the exploitation that KrishiSetu is designed to end.

1.2  The Role of Predatory Middlemen
The traditional mandi (market yard) system, while intended to protect farmers, has been captured by a class of licensed commission agents who wield disproportionate power. These intermediaries:
●	Control market access: Farmers without established relationships are often denied the best auction lots.
●	Delay payments: Payment cycles of 15–30 days are common, forcing farmers into debt cycles.
●	Manipulate price discovery: Without access to real-time APMC (Agricultural Produce Market Committee) rates, farmers cannot validate whether the price offered is fair.
●	Charge opaque commissions: Commission rates vary from 4% to 10%, often undisclosed at the point of sale.

The consequences cascade: farmers borrow money to survive between harvests, cannot invest in better inputs, and remain trapped in a cycle of subsistence agriculture. The NSSO 77th Round Report confirms that over 52% of agricultural households are indebted, with average household debt exceeding ₹74,000.

1.3  The Rural Youth Employment Crisis
Compounding the income crisis is a parallel employment crisis affecting rural youth. As mechanisation increases and traditional farm labour decreases, technically skilled rural youth — tractor mechanics, irrigation technicians, cold-storage operators, harvesting crew — find themselves without structured access to local gig-work opportunities.

The ILO India Report on Rural Youth Employment Challenges documents a trend of forced urban migration: young workers leave villages not by choice but because no platform exists to match their skills to proximate agricultural demand. This brain-drain of rural skills further weakens village economies and increases urban pressure.

KrishiSetu addresses both crises simultaneously — the income gap for farmers and the employment gap for rural youth — within a single, unified digital platform.

 
2. The Three Pillars of KrishiSetu
KrishiSetu is not a single-feature application. It is an integrated ecosystem built on three interdependent pillars, each solving a specific dimension of the agricultural livelihood problem. Together, they create a flywheel: transparent prices attract buyers, buyers attract sellers, and transactions generate local employment.

Pillar 1 — FarmConnect: The Direct B2B Digital Marketplace
What it is
FarmConnect is a business-to-business (B2B) digital marketplace that directly connects farmers and farmer producer organisations (FPOs) with wholesale buyers, institutional buyers (hotels, restaurants, food processors), and export aggregators — eliminating commission agents from the transaction entirely.

How it works
●	Farmers list produce: Crop type, quantity (in quintals), expected harvest date, quality grade, and location — all entered through a simple, visually guided interface designed for low-digital-literacy users.
●	Buyers browse and bid: Verified wholesale buyers browse active listings, filtered by region, commodity, and quantity. They submit purchase offers directly.
●	Price transparency at the moment of decision: Every offer displayed to the farmer is shown alongside the live APMC market rate for that commodity — pulled from the Government APMC Data API (data.gov.in). The farmer sees, in real-time: 'Market rate today: ₹14/kg • Buyer offer: ₹11/kg'. This empowers negotiation before acceptance.
●	Smart order management: Accepted orders generate a digital contract with agreed price, quantity, delivery date, and payment terms, stored on the platform for dispute resolution.
●	Ratings and trust: Both farmers and buyers accumulate reputation scores based on transaction history, payment timeliness, and produce quality — building a trustworthy marketplace over time.

The problem it solves
FarmConnect breaks the information monopoly that middlemen exploit. When a farmer knows the market rate, a buyer offering 21% below it must justify or increase the offer. Negotiations shift from blind acceptance to informed decision-making. The farmer transitions from price-taker to price-maker.

For buyers, FarmConnect provides a traceable, direct supply chain. They know who grew the produce, where, and under what conditions — reducing supply chain risk and meeting the growing corporate demand for provenance transparency.

Component	Description
Users	Small & marginal farmers, Farmer Producer Organisations (FPOs), Wholesale buyers, Food processors, Hotels & restaurants
Key Feature	Side-by-side display of buyer offer vs. live APMC mandi rate at the point of decision
Impact	Increases farmer's net realisation per quintal by eliminating intermediary commissions (typically 4–10% per layer)
Data Source	Government APMC Open Data API — data.gov.in (real, publicly available, not simulated)

Pillar 2 — PriceWatch: The Live APMC Market Rate Dashboard
What it is
PriceWatch is a real-time price intelligence dashboard that fetches, displays, and contextualises live commodity prices from APMC mandis across different regions, using the Government of India's open data infrastructure at data.gov.in.

How it works
●	Live data integration: The backend queries the APMC Govt. Data API continuously, fetching commodity-wise, mandi-wise daily price data. The data includes minimum price, maximum price, and modal (most common) price.
●	Regional filtering: Farmers can filter by their district or state to see the most relevant mandis — the ones they could realistically access or compare against.
●	Market trend indicators: PriceWatch shows week-on-week price trends (e.g., 'Tomatoes: Up 15% this week'), helping farmers make planting and selling timing decisions.
●	Offline fallback: Because rural internet connectivity is unreliable, PriceWatch implements a local JSON fallback cache. If the live API is unavailable, the system serves the last-known daily rates with a clear 'As of [date]' timestamp — so farmers always have some price reference rather than none.
●	Crop Quality Indicators: Beyond price, PriceWatch surfaces quality-related data (where available) from APMC records, helping buyers assess regional produce standards.

The problem it solves
Price discovery is the single most powerful tool a farmer can have. Without it, every transaction is a negotiation in the dark. PriceWatch floods that darkness with light — giving every farmer with a smartphone the same market intelligence that was previously available only to large traders and aggregators.

Unlike apps that simulate or approximate mandi prices, PriceWatch uses real government data — the same data the mandis themselves submit. This is not a demo feature; it is production-grade price intelligence.

Component	Description
Users	Farmers (pre-sale price discovery), Buyers (source the cheapest regional supply), Agri-journalists & researchers
Key Feature	Real-time commodity prices from actual APMC mandis, with week-on-week trend indicators
