3. SDG Mapping: KrishiSetu's Global Development Alignment
KrishiSetu is not merely a commercial product — it is a development intervention. Its design, features, and impact pathways are directly aligned with three of the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals. Below is a detailed mapping of how each platform component contributes to each SDG target.

SDG	Goal	KrishiSetu's Contribution
SDG 1	No Poverty	By increasing farmer income and ensuring fair market prices through elimination of predatory middlemen, KrishiSetu directly combats rural poverty — the primary driver of income inequality in agrarian India. SkillSetu further creates employment for rural youth, adding additional income streams to families below the poverty line.
SDG 2	Zero Hunger	A transparent supply chain incentivises greater agricultural production by assuring farmers of fair returns on their labour. When farmers earn more, they reinvest in better seeds, irrigation, and practices — increasing yields and food availability. FarmConnect also reduces post-harvest losses by directly linking produce to buyers faster.
SDG 8	Decent Work & Economic Growth	SkillSetu directly generates rural employment by matching technically-skilled youth (mechanics, cold-storage operators, equipment technicians) with local agri-sector gig opportunities. This reduces forced urban migration and drives inclusive economic growth within rural communities, contributing to India's agricultural GDP.

3.1  SDG 1 — No Poverty
Target 1.1 asks that by 2030, all people everywhere living in extreme poverty are eradicated. Target 1.4 calls for ensuring all people have access to economic resources, including access to markets.

KrishiSetu directly operationalises these targets. FarmConnect restores the farmer's claim to the market price, rather than the middleman's offer price. When a farmer selling 10 quintals of tomatoes at ₹14/kg (market rate) instead of ₹8/kg (middleman offer) earns ₹6,000 more per transaction, that surplus is the difference between debt and dignity.

SkillSetu contributes an additional income stream for rural households: a tractor mechanic earning ₹500/day for 60 working days a year generates ₹30,000 in supplemental income — enough to fund a child's education or eliminate a seasonal loan.

3.2  SDG 2 — Zero Hunger
Target 2.3 calls for doubling the agricultural productivity and incomes of small-scale food producers. Target 2.c demands correction of market distortions in agricultural commodity markets.

PriceWatch directly addresses market distortions by democratising price data. When all market participants have access to the same price information — a condition economists call price transparency — markets become more efficient and prices more equitable.

A farmer who earns more will invest more: better seeds, fertiliser, irrigation, and pest management. This productivity investment, multiplied across millions of small farmers, compounds into a national-level food security improvement. Furthermore, FarmConnect's direct linkage reduces post-harvest losses (currently estimated at 15–20% of total production in India) by connecting farmers to buyers faster, reducing the time produce spends in transit through intermediary hands.

3.3  SDG 8 — Decent Work and Economic Growth
Target 8.3 promotes policies that support decent job creation and growing enterprises in rural economies. Target 8.6 calls for substantially reducing the proportion of youth not in employment, education, or training.

SkillSetu is the most direct embodiment of SDG 8. It creates a structured, transparent labour market for rural agricultural skills — skills that currently exist in abundance but are deployed inefficiently due to information gaps. By giving rural youth access to a job board calibrated to their skills and proximity, KrishiSetu enables them to build careers in agriculture rather than abandoning their communities.

The broader platform also contributes to SDG 8.10 (access to financial services and markets for all) by creating digital transaction records for farmers and workers — records that could eventually be used to access formal credit, insurance, and government welfare schemes that currently require income documentation these populations cannot produce.

KrishiSetu is one of the few agritech solutions that simultaneously targets SDG 1, SDG 2, and SDG 8 — not as a marketing claim, but as a direct outcome of its three-pillar architecture.

4. Summary
The agricultural crisis in India is fundamentally an information crisis. Farmers lack price information. Rural workers lack employment information. Buyers lack supply chain transparency. KrishiSetu provides all three — in one platform, on one device, accessible even on intermittent rural internet.

By building on real government data (APMC Open API), proven web technologies (React PWA + Node.js + PostgreSQL), and human-centred design principles (colour-coded UX for low-literacy users, voice-first application flow), KrishiSetu is not a speculative prototype — it is an immediately deployable solution to a documented, data-evidenced problem.

The 25–35% profit gap is not inevitable. KrishiSetu closes it, one transparent transaction at a time.

